UPDATE regions SET generated_intro = $aud$The Great Southern unfolds across Western Australia's lower reaches like a geological textbook written in granite and karri. This is where the continent's southwestern corner begins its slow descent toward the Southern Ocean, creating a landscape of abrupt transitions: wheat fields that terminate at towering forests, granite peaks that rise from farmland, and rivers that carve deep valleys before meeting wild coastlines. Albany anchors the region's eastern edge, its harbour sheltered by the same headlands that once provided the last glimpse of Australia for departing ANZAC troops. Denmark sits where the Denmark River meets Wilson Inlet, surrounded by karri forests that tower over small farms and emerging vineyards. Mount Barker occupies the region's elevated interior, its undulating countryside now stitched with vine rows where sheep once grazed.

The wine revolution that began here in the 1970s has matured into something more nuanced than mere viticulture. Alkoomi Wines, established by the Lange family near Frankland River, demonstrates the region's capacity for both riesling and cabernet sauvignon—an unusual pairing that speaks to the complexity of local microclimates. Forest Hill Vineyard produces elegant pinot noir from Denmark's cooler pockets, while Harewood Estate near Denmark focuses on single-vineyard expressions that reflect their specific slice of granite-over-clay country. These aren't vanity projects or corporate ventures; they represent farming families who recognised that their marginal sheep country might excel at something entirely different. Castelli Estate and Frankland Estate continue this theme, with Singlefile Wines pushing the boundaries further still, crafting wines that taste distinctly of this corner of Australia rather than anywhere else.

The region's seasons dictate more than just harvest timing. Winter brings the rains that green the granite outcrops and fill the catchments that feed Denmark's rivers and Albany's reservoirs. This is when the Stirling Range reveals its temperamental character—Bluff Knoll can be shrouded in cloud for days, then emerge crystalline and snow-dusted. Spring transforms the countryside into wildflower country, with banksia and grevillea species that exist nowhere else. The Bibbulmun Track, which terminates in Albany after its thousand-kilometre journey from Perth, shows its finest form during these months when water is plentiful and temperatures moderate. Summer demands respect; this is granite country, and exposed rock radiates heat that can make midday hiking punishing. Autumn brings the harvest, but also the region's most settled weather—clear days and cool nights that extend well into May.

Time here moves at the pace of seasonal work rather than tourist schedules. Morning might begin at Forest Hill Vineyard, where the tasting room overlooks Denmark's rolling countryside, followed by a drive through the karri forests that separate Denmark from Albany. The Lake House Denmark offers a different perspective entirely—lunch overlooking Wilson Inlet, where black swans patrol waters that reflect the surrounding forest canopy. Afternoon could involve the climb to Bluff Knoll, the Stirling Range's highest peak, where the view encompasses wheat country to the north and Southern Ocean to the south. Evening settles naturally around one of the region's wine estates, perhaps Harewood or Rockcliffe, where the focus remains on the wine itself rather than elaborate hospitality infrastructure.

What distinguishes the Great Southern from Margaret River to the west or the Grampians to the east is its resistance to tourism monoculture. This remains working country where wine production coexists with grain farming, timber harvesting, and fishing. Albany's port still handles grain exports from the inland wheat belt, and Denmark's sawmill continues processing karri logs alongside the boutique wineries. The accommodation reflects this practical character: Stirling Range Homestead offers farm-stay accommodation that connects visitors to the agricultural reality of the region, while Denmark River Cottage provides river-access lodging that feels integral to its landscape rather than imposed upon it. The region's independent character extends to its hospitality—venues like those scattered around Mount Barker and Denmark operate as extensions of their owners' agricultural enterprises rather than standalone tourism businesses. This integration of production, landscape, and hospitality creates something more grounded than many wine regions achieve, a sense that the visitor is encountering a place that exists for its own reasons rather than theirs.$aud$, long_description = $aud$The Great Southern unfolds across Western Australia's lower reaches like a geological textbook written in granite and karri. This is where the continent's southwestern corner begins its slow descent toward the Southern Ocean, creating a landscape of abrupt transitions: wheat fields that terminate at towering forests, granite peaks that rise from farmland, and rivers that carve deep valleys before meeting wild coastlines. Albany anchors the region's eastern edge, its harbour sheltered by the same headlands that once provided the last glimpse of Australia for departing ANZAC troops. Denmark sits where the Denmark River meets Wilson Inlet, surrounded by karri forests that tower over small farms and emerging vineyards. Mount Barker occupies the region's elevated interior, its undulating countryside no